node.text:
@wildbirdresearch is only a month away from Owl research season, and while we focus on Northern Saw-whet Owls, we tend to get a few resident Eastern Screech Owls. I’d say it’s about even between red and gray morph screech owls that we get, but I’d have to say I’m more of a red morph kind of guy.  Soon enough will see how our local populations did during the breeding season; fingers crossed it’s a good year.

For questions about handling, research, or why we don’t show how we catch birds refer to my post on May 16th.

node.text: I figured I’d post a little portrait series to go along with the reel I posted of Northern Cardinals. While they might be the most familiar bird in the US, they have complexities hiding within their bright red plumage. Males and females express their fitness level in the intensity of red coloration in their breast (males) and the underwing coloration (females). This helps Cardinals choose mates, territory and shows to each other their abilities as parents. In the first photo, you see a nice bright red male, next to a female, and lastly, a young bird born this year. It takes a little bit of time to get to that bright red.

node.text:
The Northern Cardinal is one of our most recognizable birds in the US, often found at feeders and back yards. Their red plumage is uniform but complex in ways. Unlike many birds, their plumage is not structural coloration, and it comes from their diet. The red looks similar between individuals, but to Cardinals, they can see when the red is richer in color and signals health and status. Studies have shown brighter individuals have larger territories and hold onto many favorable habitats with richer resources. The first two clips are adult male birds, both brilliant red. Next is a young male in fall; you can see his red plumage is coming in nicely, but the bill coloration is still changing. Next is a young juvenile; when they are first born, you can’t tell if they’re male or female, but they’ll begin to show their secrets; this was a young male. Lastly is a female, females show their health in two ways they have a peach coloration in their underwing. The brighter it is, the healthier they are, again this is subtle to our eyes, and they can also show differences in the black coloration on their face masks. 

For information on handling, research, or why I don’t show how we capture birds, refer to my post on May 16th.

node.text: Over the last few days, I’ve been soaking in the visits of a juvenile male Ruby-throated Hummingbird. Soon I know I’ll lose these splendid flyers to their migration southward. All 3 grams of them will soon travel down the coast, headed for Central America. Many will cross the Gulf of Mexico in a single flight, truly one of nature’s wonders. If you swipe, you get to see a mature male and the single feather of a juvenile, remarkable how so many changes for them in less than a year, traveling thousands of miles and molting in a throat of rubies.

node.text: The Plain-capped Starthroat is a bit of an unassuming species in the tropics. It’s large and very long billed, but a little plain. Now I’m not calling it plain because I enjoy their almost stretched-out Ruby-throated Hummingbird appearance. Still, when there’s a swarm of hummingbirds species looking like miniature Jackson Pollock paintings, you can get a little lost. This species is found along the pacific coast from Mexico all the way to Panama, often found in drier habitats along the coast.

node.text: Well, it seemed like everyone wanted a dose of Hummingbirds, and I’ll be honest, I wanted an excuse to look through old material. The Crowned Woodnymph is a wide-ranging species found in many Central and South American countries. Their brilliant crown and throat may be used for signaling within the rainforest. At a certain angle, the tiny hummingbird disappears with their dark overall plumage, but then they turn their body, revealing this incredible shimmering look. The signaling might be for territory or breeding, but whichever it is, it’s quite a show.

node.text: As crazy as it is to believe fall migration is already happening. Neotropical migrants are gathering resources to begin their migration back to their winter homes. Many of them look very different now than they did in their best spring outfits. A few warblers, though, will look exactly the same. The Black-throated Blue Warbler is one of those anomalies. At one time, it was believed the female (second slide) was a different species Pine-swamp Warbler, eventually though they figured it out.

node.text: The American Goldfinch is a common well-known breeder in the United States, but most don’t know they’re incredibly dynamic in their breeding. Many common species of birds that we enjoy in the temperate zone all year long (think of you common backyard feeder birds) get an early start on breeding, beating the migrating species for nest-site selection and resources. American Goldfinches are unique in that they’re one of the latest breeders, not till July often, meaning we’ve just started to see their babies. We believe this is tied to their multiple molt cycles and the blooming of thistle. With such a late schedule, these birds often only get one clutch of eggs in. Experienced females, though, will lay eggs with a male, leave him to care for that set of chicks, and find a new male partner to get two broods in. We saw this occur this week, with a few females with active brood patches to incubate eggs, even one female about to lay an egg. Pretty amazing the small intricacies in the bird world.

node.text: Many birds don’t have such elegance when they’re younger, and they often have muted colors to help hide them while they mature with the help of their parents. The Eastern Bluebird, in my option, has quite a lot of flair, even at a young age. They have their blue wings, polka dot back feathers, and an overall pearl gray color. While I find the young bluebirds charming, one can’t argue that the brilliant blue of adults is stunning. Bluebirds often remind me of the fantastic colorful species I have In my backyard.

node.text:
It’s International Owl Awareness Day, and before we know it, @wildbirdresearch will be back working with Owls. This year will be operating three stations in the greater Princeton area, and it’ll be a combination of weekday and weekend nights. Starting mid-October running through the beginning of December will be out working on Northern Saw-whet Owl migration research. We’re looking for new volunteers and field technicians for the fall; if interested, send over a CV, resume, and which position you’re looking to fulfill. The main difference is volunteers won’t be required to be at the site every night, whereas techs will need to be at every session. Correspondence can be emailed to wildbirdresearch@gmail.com

Pictured is a red-morph Eastern Screech Owl, one of the many we got last season. For training before the saw-whet season will be working with this species.

node.text:
Is that Northern Saw-whet Owl? Sure is, and @wildbirdresearch is already thinking about our upcoming owl research season. We’re hoping to operate three full capacity sites this year with full crews! That means @wildbirdresearch will be looking for new research technicians and volunteers. If you’re interested in getting involved, send us an email at wildbirdresearch@gmail.com, send us a cover letter, resume, and if you’re looking to be a tech or volunteer. For those wondering, for techs were looking for prior research and wildlife handling experience, and with volunteers, there isn’t previous experience needed.
We’re looking forward to a fun season with a lot of different research projects.
